  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2933249662" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2933249662" />
    <a title="Jenny" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7206839-jenny"><img alt="Jenny" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1622941795p2/7206839.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2933249662?book_show_action=true">Aug 22, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jenny" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jenny" href="/user/show/7206839-jenny">Jenny</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780679640516" href="/book/show/3559501-the-enchantress-of-florence">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2933249662" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11424074259376168089">This book is gorgeous, the physical book. I love the cover, so it makes me sad that I don&apos;t want to keep it because I didn&apos;t like what&apos;s inside. <br/><br/>I like the concept of this book, kind of. It reminds me of Italo Calvino&apos;s Invisible Cities, in which Marco Polo talks to Kublai Khan about the cities he&apos;s traveled through. Much of this book is Niccolo Vespucci talking to Akbar the Great about his family&apos;s past travels and intrigues. I like the setting, which is mostly Sikri and Florence in the 16th ce</span>
  <span id="freeText11424074259376168089" style="display:none">This book is gorgeous, the physical book. I love the cover, so it makes me sad that I don't want to keep it because I didn't like what's inside. <br /><br />I like the concept of this book, kind of. It reminds me of Italo Calvino's Invisible Cities, in which Marco Polo talks to Kublai Khan about the cities he's traveled through. Much of this book is Niccolo Vespucci talking to Akbar the Great about his family's past travels and intrigues. I like the setting, which is mostly Sikri and Florence in the 16th century. Rushdie's writing is astounding in this regard because he makes both settings, not just place but also time, come alive. I even like the characters and how well-rounded they are.<br /><br />Why two stars, then? <br /><br />Well, the book is overly sexual, and I really don't understand it. I get that sexuality is important, but I've never understood why, in literary fiction, there's a need for such overt sexual references. I'm not even talking about sex scenes, which at least make sense. I'm talking about references to sex acts, standard and "deviant," that come out of nowhere and are thrown into the narrative for literally no reason. <br />I think one of the themes of the novel is the power that women have over men, which is ironic because men think they're the "stronger sex," but they can be overthrown by a woman's body, which is ridiculous. This concept is best shown by a scene in which the narrator says all the women in Sikri walked around naked one day while the men remained blindfolded, so the women could see that they all had the same parts and had no reason to be jealous of each other. In the same way, men should have no reason to swoon over beauties and be Helen of Troy-ed into fighting and losing kingdoms when all women, in reality, have the same parts. I like that theme. It's truthful--I see it in the Bible, how the women are always the cause of the Israelites' idolatry, but it's not because of the women's weakness. No, it's the <i>men's</i> weakness <i>for</i> women that allows the women to be successful in calling the men over to their gods. <br />I say all that to say that it's a great theme, but it doesn't have to be so explicit. The way Rushdie writes about women and their deeds and misdeeds makes me shudder.<br /><br />I also don't like that the book is <i>so</i> filled with details. I teach my students that details make writing come alive and differentiate your essay about assumptions from someone else's essay about the same topic. But every sentence in this book, especially in the first third or so, is filled with seventeen facts. I had to reread and reread to let my mind settle around all the information. The book is more information dump, Rushdie showing off how much he can include in a 349-page book, than it is story. Because the actual story really wouldn't take up much space, as interesting as it is. <br /><br />To be a little backwards and contradictory, I also enjoyed the theme of circularity and the cyclical nature of existence. This kingdom was overthrown by this kingdom, which was overthrown by... Nothing is permanent, even a hundred-year-old empire. The Persians will overthrow them, and the Greeks will overthrow them, and the Ottomans will overthrow them. It reminds us that my life is your life, and your life is the next person's life. To paraphrase Rushdie's Vespucci, the great curse of humanity is not that we are so different but that we are all the same. There's nothing new under the sun. Nothing gold can stay. That sort of thing. <br />Finally, the theme of the power of words, language, and storytelling is always one that will impact me. Vespucci tells a story, and his story enthralls the king and changes the kingdom. <br /><br />Overall, I like the themes of this book and the core stories. I don't like the extraneous detail and the overt sexualisation of pretty much everything . When I finished, I felt, immediately, "This was so pointless." I think that, if you're going to write a book about something that's already been written about before, it has to be really impactful. Rushdie's writing is beautiful, as always, and there are lovely sentences and concepts in this book. But the book as a whole felt trite. It didn't have a "wow factor." Maybe because an Italian man going to talk to an Indian king isn't interesting anymore? I don't know. I think Rushdie could've done more with the concept, though, and made it more special. <br /><br />I can still recommend this book if you enjoy stories from the time period of the discovery of the New World and Marco Polo's travels and the Indians, Persians, and Ottomans. If you're a Rushdie fan like I am, you may be disappointed too, but you may want to read it anyway. It's definitely well-written, and it's not a difficult read, if you don't mind rereading sentences to understand who is whom. <br /><br />Overall, the two stars feel right. It was okay.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11424074259376168089" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


